      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's great to meet you. Five years of running experience, a solid 44-minute 10K under your belt, and you're doing the smart thing — coming back carefully after plantar fasciitis rather than rushing it. That kind of patience is genuinely hard, and it matters.\n\nBefore I lay out the full plan, I want to check in with you briefly: **what does \"getting back\" mean to you right now?** Is it simply moving without pain again, rebuilding toward that 10K fitness, or something else? That'll help me frame this the right way.\n\nThat said, you asked for a comprehensive plan, so let me give you one — with full rationale so you understand the *why* behind every decision.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture First\n\nHere's what I want you to understand before we look at a single week of training:\n\n**Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running only, with walking breaks if there's any foot pain.** That's the non-negotiable foundation everything is built on. Plantar fasciitis is notoriously sensitive to load spikes — the tissue needs progressive, consistent stress to adapt, not aggressive pushes. The plan below respects that completely.\n\nYour pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 gives us your training paces, but I want to be honest with you: **your current fitness is almost certainly lower than that after the layoff.** That's not a problem — it's just reality, and it's exactly why we're starting conservatively. The paces below are your *ceiling* right now, not your target.\n\n**No speed work, no threshold, no intervals** until you're cleared. Those paces exist in your profile for reference, but they're not part of this plan yet.\n\n---\n\n## Your Training Paces (Physiotherapist-Cleared Phase)\n\n| Type | Pace Range | Status |\n|------|-----------|--------|\n| Easy | 5:24 – 5:58 /km | ✅ Active — use the **slow end** (5:45–5:58) |\n| Marathon | 4:44 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Threshold | 4:29 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Interval | 4:12 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n| Repetition | 3:57 /km | \uD83D\uDD12 Locked |\n\n> **Why the slow end of easy?** Your recent runs have all been at 5:58/km — that's your body telling you something. Plantar fasciitis responds poorly to pace pressure. Staying at the comfortable end of easy keeps the foot load manageable while still building aerobic fitness. There's no fitness lost by going slower right now; there's a lot to lose by going too fast.\n\n---\n\n## Plan Structure: 3 Phases\n\n| Phase | Duration | Focus | Weekly Runs |\n|-------|----------|-------|-------------|\n| **Phase 1: Tissue Tolerance** | Weeks 1–4 | Re-establish consistent running, zero pain | 3 days |\n| **Phase 2: Base Rebuild** | Weeks 5–8 | Extend duration, introduce continuous running | 3 days |\n| **Phase 3: Transition** | Weeks 9–12 | Build toward normal easy running, await clearance | 3 days |\n\n**3 days/week maximum** as you requested — Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday (long run). Rest days between every run session. This isn't just preference; for plantar fasciitis recovery, the off days are when the fascia actually adapts and strengthens.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1: Tissue Tolerance (Weeks 1–4)\n\n**Goal:** Three consistent, pain-free runs per week. Duration matters more than distance. Walking breaks are a tool, not a failure.\n\n**The 10% rule applies to total weekly minutes, not just distance.** Your recent week was approximately 38 minutes of running across 3 sessions. We'll build from there.\n\n### Week 1 *(Starting point — mirrors your recent training)*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min | Run/walk as needed | 5:45–5:58/km when running |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 18 min | Run/walk as needed | 5:45–5:58/km when running |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min | Run/walk as needed | Long run — your ceiling for now |\n| **Total** | | **~53 min** | | |\n\n### Week 2\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| **Total** | | **~55 min** | | |\n\n### Week 3\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min | Run/walk as needed | |\n| **Total** | | **~58 min** | | |\n\n### Week 4 — Deload ⬇️\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min | Easy, relaxed | Pull back intentionally |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min | Easy, relaxed | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min | Easy, relaxed | |\n| **Total** | | **~50 min** | | |\n\n> **Why a deload in Week 4?** Every 3–4 weeks, we deliberately reduce load. This isn't lost fitness — it's when your body actually consolidates the adaptations from the previous three weeks. Skipping deloads is one of the most common reasons runners get re-injured.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Base Rebuild (Weeks 5–8)\n\n**Goal:** Transition toward continuous running (fewer walk breaks), extend total weekly time modestly. Your physiotherapist clearance may evolve here — check in with them around Week 5–6.\n\n> ⚠️ **Important:** The duration increases below assume you remain pain-free through Phase 1. If foot pain returns at any point, we pause and reassess. The plan adapts to you, not the other way around.\n\n### Week 5\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | Aim for continuous | Walk if needed |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Aim for continuous | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min | Continuous | |\n| **Total** | | **~60 min** | | |\n\n### Week 6\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | Continuous | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 22 min | Continuous | Small step up |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 25 min | Continuous | First extension beyond 20 min |\n| **Total** | | **~67 min** | | |\n\n> **Why extend Saturday first?** The long run is where aerobic base is built most efficiently. By extending Saturday before the weekday runs, we get the biggest physiological return with the least cumulative load on the foot.\n\n### Week 7\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 22 min | Continuous | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 22 min | Continuous | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 28 min | Continuous | |\n| **Total** | | **~72 min** | | |\n\n### Week 8 — Deload ⬇️\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min | Easy | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | Easy | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 22 min | Easy | |\n| **Total** | | **~60 min** | | |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3: Transition (Weeks 9–12)\n\n**Goal:** Rebuild toward a normal easy running week (~3 hours/week at easy pace). Begin conversations with your physiotherapist about returning to structured training.\n\nBy this phase, if things have gone well, you'll be running continuously and pain-free. This is also when we'd start planning your *next* phase — whether that's a 10K build, a new race goal, or something else entirely.\n\n### Week 9\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 25 min | Continuous | 5:30–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 25 min | Continuous | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 32 min | Continuous | |\n| **Total** | | **~82 min** | | |\n\n### Week 10\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 27 min | Continuous | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 27 min | Continuous | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 35 min | Continuous | |\n| **Total** | | **~89 min** | | |\n\n### Week 11\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 28 min | Continuous | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 28 min | Continuous | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 38 min | Continuous | |\n| **Total** | | **~94 min** | | |\n\n### Week 12 — Deload + Reassessment ⬇️\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Type | Notes |\n|-----|---------|----------|------|-------|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 22 min | Easy | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 25 min | Easy | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 30 min | Easy | |\n| **Total** | | **~77 min** | | |\n\n---\n\n## Key Coaching Principles for This Plan\n\n### \uD83E\uDDB6 The Foot Pain Rule — Non-Negotiable\nIf you feel **any foot pain during a run**, walk immediately. Don't try to run through it. This isn't weakness — it's the smartest thing you can do. Plantar fasciitis that flares mid-run and gets pushed through can set recovery back weeks. Walking breaks are built into this plan as a legitimate tool.\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC8 The 10% Guardrail\nWeekly volume (in minutes) never increases more than 10% week-over-week, except into deload weeks. This isn't arbitrary — connective tissue like the plantar fascia adapts more slowly than muscle or cardiovascular fitness. The aerobic system will feel ready before the foot is ready. Trust the slower timeline.\n\n### \uD83D\uDE34 Rest Days Are Training Days\nThe days between your runs are when your fascia is actually remodeling and strengthening. Three days of running with full recovery beats five days of running with accumulated fatigue every time at this stage.\n\n### \uD83E\uDE7A Physiotherapist Check-ins\nI'd suggest checking in with your physio at:\n- **End of Week 4** — before extending beyond 20 minutes\n- **End of Week 8** — before Phase 3, and to discuss return to structured training\n- **Any time foot pain returns** — don't wait for a scheduled check-in\n\n---\n\n## What Comes After Week 12?\n\nIf you're pain-free and running continuously by Week 12, you'll be in a great position to start a proper base-building phase — and eventually, a 10K training block. Your VDOT of 46.5 is a real number that reflects real fitness you've built. It'll come back faster than you think once the foundation is solid.\n\n---\n\n**One question to close:** How does this feel when you look at it? Is there anything about the structure — the pacing, the progression, the deload weeks — that you'd want to talk through or adjust?"
        }
